quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
  2,77,"Do they not know that Allah knows whatever they keep secret and whatever they make public?"
  2,78,"And among them{1}are illiterates who do not know the Scripture, other than fancies, and they only speculate.",footnotes:1:The Jews.
  2,79,"So woe to those who scribe the Scripture with their own hands and then say, “This is from Allah,” that they may purchase, in exchange for it, a small price. Woe to them on account of what their hands have written, and woe to them on account of what they earn{1}.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from past tense to present tense.
  2,80,"And they said, “The Fire will not touch us except for a few days.” Say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Have you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>taken a covenant from Allah—so Allah will never break His covenant—or are you saying about Allah what you do not know?”"
  2,81,"Yes indeed, whoever has earned an evil deed and whose <span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Nafie’ and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…whose offenses have surrounded…”</span>
  2,82,"But those who have attained faith and have done righteous deeds—those are the fellows of the Garden<i class=""s"">(of Paradise) </i>; therein they abide."
  2,83,"And recall when We took a pledge from the Children of Israel: “<span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Hamza and Al-Kesa’i read it as: “They shall worship…”</span>,footnotes:2:The Qur’an always uses verb ‘to bring’ rather than verb ‘to give’ in association with charity; this should be pondered by the reader.,footnotes:3:The Arabic word used is <i>zakāt</i>, which denotes purification and growth.,footnotes:4:A grammatical shift from 3<sup><small>rd</small></sup> person to 2<sup><small>nd</small></sup> person.
